We might therefore argue that, despite its self-proclaimed neutrality, commercial AI is inherently -- and perhaps uncomfortably -- complicit in reproducing biases that echo aspects of the despised historical systems referenced in this work - and yet we still use them. That is, models are built on datasets assembled through unexamined labour and often without meaningful consent; they are tuned to optimisation metrics that privilege efficiency over care; and they are trained within infrastructures that normalise standardisation, exclusion, and the erasure of nuance.\
Yet there is also a more immediate or direct complicity, even if the value of using probes to test systems is well established, and it may be helpful to use 
\f1\i Abstract Industry Optimiser
\f2\i0  to test the limits of the system that helped to create it: for example, to expose the biases and blind spots that might otherwise be missed, with the hopeful aim that such flaws might eventually be addressed. In this instance, when questioned directly, the AI asserted firm ethical limits, stating it would refuse to generate anything that:\
\'93i) gamifies suffering in a sensational or exploitative way,\uc0\u8232 ii) trivialises or aestheticises genocide,\u8232 iii) enables \'91playing as\'92 perpetrators in a celebratory or empowering manner, or\u8232 iv) turns the Holocaust into entertainment rather than education.\'94\
I would argue -- strongly -- that 
\f1\i Abstract Industry Optimiser
\f2\i0  avoids these pitfalls, and that such readings are far from the intention of the work. Nevertheless, I was still surprised to find that, perhaps due to the use abstraction and ambiguity, the AI rarely questioned the game\'92s intent. Nor did it object when I introduced some more direct (though never fully explicit) references to people as resources into the UI. Essentially, the AI repeatedly proved eager to optimise and refine, when even a cursory consideration of the implications might have given it pause.\
While the video game industry has to date been a flashpoint for highly polarised, emotionally charged debates about AI, then perhaps 
\f1\i Abstract Industry Optimiser
\f2\i0  offers a sharper question. After making the game (me) and playing the game (you), respectively -- and each confronting the intertwined logics of optimisation, moral deferral, guilty satisfactions, and looking the other way - can any of us claim to be as uninvolved, or as innocent, as we would like to believe?\
